* Summer: April (巳), May (午), June (未) – fire, fire, earth
* Autumn: July (申), August (酉), September (戌) – metal, metal, earth
* Winter: October (亥), November (子), December (丑) – water, water, earth

The cyclic pairing of the heavenly stems and earthly branches produces 60 unique combinations (e.g., 甲寅 or 乙卯), forming the {{ill|Sexagenary cycle|ja|干支|qq=draft|qq=draft}}.

== Calendar ==
The Yin-Yang Five Elements calendar and its associated divination system consider the year beginning with {{ill|Lichun|ja|立春|qq=draft|qq=draft}}, around February 4 in the Gregorian calendar. Months start not on the first day but on one of the {{ill|solar term|ja|二十四節気|lt=24 solar terms|qq=draft|qq=draft}}, marking seasonal transitions.

Examples of monthly beginnings:
* {{ill|Lichun|ja|立春|qq=draft|qq=draft}} (Beginning of Spring): around February 4
* {{ill|Keichitsu|ja|啓蟄|qq=draft|qq=draft}} (Awakening of Insects): around March 6
* {{ill|Shōkan|ja|小寒|qq=draft|qq=draft}} (Lesser Cold): around January 5

During this calendar system, the year's zodiac changes at ''shōkan,'' so the period from January 5 to February 3 still belongs to the preceding year’s zodiac.

== Logic of Yin-Yang and Five Elements ==
The theory combines {{ill|Yin and Yang|ja|陰陽思想|1=Yin and yang|lt=Yin-Yang Theory|qq=draft|qq=draft}} and {{ill|Wuxing (Chinese philosophy)|lt=Five Elements|ja|五行|qq=draft|qq=draft}} to explain the natural world. Its origins trace to ''The Four Seasons'' chapter in ''{{ill|Guanzi|ja|管子|qq=draft|qq=draft}}'' and its framework relies on combinations derived from the ''I Ching''.

'''Yin and Yang''': These represent dual forces like positive and negative, light and dark, or male and female. Their interaction governs balance and cyclic transformation.

'''Five Elements''': Originating from ancient governance principles, the elements correspond to five planets: Mercury (water), Venus (metal), Mars (fire), Jupiter (wood), and Saturn (earth).

=== Five Elements Interactions ===
{{Main|{{ill|Wuxing (Chinese philosophy)|lt=Five Elements|ja|五行|qq=draft|qq=draft}}}}
Interactions are categorized as:
* '''Mutual Generation (相生)''': Enhancing relationships, such as wood generating fire, which produces ash (earth), from which metal is extracted.
* '''Mutual Restraint (相剋)''': Regulating relationships, such as water extinguishing fire, which melts metal.

== Influence in Japan ==
Introduced alongside {{ill|Calendrical systems|ja|暦法|qq=draft|qq=draft}} in the 5th and 6th centuries, the theory influenced {{ill|Ritsuryō|ja|律令|qq=draft|qq=draft}} governance and gave rise to {{ill|Onmyōdō|ja|陰陽道|qq=draft|qq=draft}}, incorporating {{ill|Daoist magic|ja|道教|qq=draft|qq=draft}} and evolving into uniquely Japanese practices.

Seasonal customs like the New Year (春, associated with wood) and Bon Festival (秋, associated with water) reflect its cultural integration, influencing rituals like {{ill|Tōrō nagashi|ja|燈籠流し|qq=draft|qq=draft}}.

== References ==
* Kobayashi Nobuaki, ''Research on Yin-Yang and Five Elements in Early China,'' Kodansha, 1951.

